<head>
<title>Banned in the U.S.</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Banned Information in the U.S.</h1>

<p>Here is a list of things on the Internet that the U.S. government has
made it illegal for you to see. <b>Revolution</b> extends a hearty welcome
to U.S. citizens who have defied their government's tyranny to view these
pages.</p>

<ul>

<li><img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
	href="http://www.eff.org/BlueRibbon/sites.html">EFF's
	list of banned sites</a> includes the Venus di Milo,
	<cite>Huckleberry Finn</cite> and numerous other examples</li>

<li>the Bible, especially the Old Testament, which has numerous prohibited
descriptions of indecent behavior, including adultery, sodomy, inbreeding,
masturbation and just plain sex</li>

<li><img src="/images/news.gif" alt="[NEWS]"><a
href="news:alt.binaries.pictures.erotica">alt.binaries.pictures.erotica</a>
is one of several Usenet news groups dedicated to "filthy, indecent, lewd or
lascivious" images.</li>

<li>World Wide Web search engines, like <img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]">
<a href="http://www.infoseek.com/">InfoSeek</a>, because their databases
contain titles that are prohibited</li>

<li><img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
	href="http://www.playboy.com/">Playboy</a> magazine</li>

<li><img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
	href="http://www.penthousemag.com/">Penthouse</a> magazine</li>

<li><img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
	href="http://mosaic.echonyc.com/~rzacks/">Sex in History</a></li>

<li>Much anthropological technical literature, for example,
 <img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
href="http://osf1.gmu.edu/~herwin/diamond.txt">Jared Diamond's
<cite>The Third Chimpanzee</cite></a>.</li>

<li>Controversial religious scholarship, for example
 <img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
href="http://osf1.gmu.edu/~herwin/mark.txt">Morton Smith's discovery of
a letter from Clement</a></li>

<li>The following statement, which is fully intended to annoy Sen. James Exon:
Jim Exon is an asshole.</li>

</ul>

<p>All the above would be legal for you to see if they were put on paper.
The U.S. has passed a law making them illegal in electronic form.</p>

