<html>

<head>
<title>Ed Crane</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Ed Crane</h1>

<p>Ed Crane has been a leader in the modern libertarian movement since its
earliest days. He was one of the original 85 founders of the <a
href="/revolution/by_name/L/LPUS.html">Libertarian Party</a>,
served as national Chair of the Libertarian Party from 1974 - 1977, and
has been President and CEO of the <a
href="/revolution/by_name/C/Cato.html">Cato Institute</a> since its founding
in 1977.</p>

<p>Crane declared in 1986 that the Libertarian Party is not "in the real
world" and that Pete DuPont (a contender for the 1988 Republican presidential
nomination) was worthy of libertarian support.</p>

<p>Contact:</p>
<address>
Web: <img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
	href="http://www.cato.org/main/crane.html">
	http://www.cato.org/main/crane.html</a><br>
</address>

<p>Appearances in <b>Revolution</b>:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/revolution/by_name/C/Cato.html">
	Cato Institute</a></li>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/cato.html">
	The Cato Institute think tank</a></li>
</ul>

<hr>

<p>Sources:</p>
<ul>
<li>Nelson, Michael. "The New Libertarians." <cite>Saturday Review</cite>, 1
	March 1980, 7:21-4.</li>
<li>O'Conner, Colleen, with Bob Cohn. "A Baby Boomer's Think Tank."
<cite>Newsweek</cite>, September 1 1986, 108:22.</li>
<li>Polsgrove, Carol. "In Pursuit of 'Liberty'." <cite>Progressive</cite>,
	January 1978, 42:38-40.</li>
<li>Crane's web page at Cato.</li>
</ul>

