<html>
<head>
<title>Don Gorman</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Don Gorman</h1>

<p>New Hampshire state legislator Don Gorman is a leading
<a href="/revolution/by_name/L/LPUS.html">Libertarian Party</a> activist in
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/nh/">New Hampshire</a>.
He served as a Republican in the state house from 1973 to 1976. In 1992,
he ran and won his house seat as a Libertarian. He was re-elected in 1994.</p>

<p>In May 1996, Gorman announced plans to run for Speaker of the House.
In June, a law he sponsored went into effect, ending random drunk-driving
roadblocks.</p>

<p>Appearances in <b>Revolution</b>:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/lpnh/1992.html">
	1992 New Hampshire election results</a>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/election/1994/">
	1994 election results</a></li>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/lpnh/luce.html">
	New Hampshire governor appoints Libertarian</a>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/lpnh/gorman.html">
	Libertarian announces run for Speaker</a>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/lpus/lpnh/roadblocks.html">
	Libertarian law ends random roadblocks</a></li>
</ul>

