<html>

<head>
<title>Robert Nozick</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Robert Nozick (1939 - )</h1>

<p>Robert Nozick is one of the most influential figures in the history of the
modern libertarian movement. His 1975 book <cite>Anarchy, State and
Utopia</cite> was one of three books defining early libertarian philosophy, the
other two being <a
href="/revolution/by_name/R/MurrayRothbard.html">Rothbard's</a>
<cite>Libertarian Manifesto</cite> and <a
href="/revolution/by_name/H/JohnHospers.html">Hospers'</a>
<cite>Libertarianism</cite>.</p>

<p><cite>Anarchy, State and Utopia</cite> argued that inequality is not unjust,
and that egalitarianism was inherently unjust because it must rely on the use
of force.</p>

<p>Nozick won a full professorship in philosophy at Harvard University at age
30 in 1969.</p>

<p>Appearances in <b>Revolution</b>:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/revolution/philosophy/books.html">
	Books on libertarian philosophy</a></li>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/magarts.html">
	Magazine articles on Libertarians</a></li>
</ul>

<hr>

<p>Sources:</p>
<ul>
<li>Woodward, Kenneth. "You're Entitled." <cite>Newsweek</cite>, March 31 1975,
85:81.
</ul>

