<html>

<head>
<title>Charles Koch</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Charles Koch</h1>

<p>Charles Koch, one of the heirs to the Koch Industries family fortune,
bankrolled some libertarian organizations. Koch became active in the
libertarian movement in 1976. He contributed millions to found the <a
href="/revolution/by_name/C/Cato.html">Cato Institute</a>, a libertarian
think tank, and funded the Students for a Libertarian
Society, a short-lived student group.</p>

<p>Charles' brother <a href="/revolution/by_name/K/DavidKoch.html">David</a>
won the 1980
<a href="/revolution/by_name/L/LPUS.html">Libertarian Party</a> nomination
for Vice President. David Koch's financial
contributions to the campaign helped the Libertarian Party in its impressive
third-party showing of nearly one million votes that year.</p>

<p>Appearances in <b>Revolution</b>:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/revolution/politics/cato.html">
	The Cato Institute</a></li>
</ul>

<hr>

<p>Sources:</p>
<ul>
<li>Nelson, Michael. "The New Libertarians." <cite>Saturday Review</cite>, 1
March 1980, 7:21-4.
</ul>

