<head>
<title>Libertarian Nobel Winners</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Libertarian Nobel Prize Winners</h1>

<p>Nobel Prize winners who have called themselves libertarian:</p>

<ul>

<li><p><a href="/revolution/by_name/H/FriedrichHayek.html">Friedrich Hayek</a>,
1974, Economics. Hayek was one of the leaders of the Austrian school of
economics.</p>

<li><p><a href="/revolution/by_name/F/MiltonFriedman.html">Milton Friedman</a>,
1976, Economics. Friedman is one of the founders of the Monetarist school of
economics, which advocates a free-market economy with strict control over the
money supply.</p>

<li><p>James Buchanan, 1986, Economics. Buchanan won the prize for developing
the "Public Choice" school of economics, which analyzes political behavior (of
voters, politicans and lobbyists) in terms of self-interest.</p>

<li><p>Kary Mullis, 1993, Chemistry. Mullis won the prize for figuring 
out how to make unlimited copies of DNA. In the Fort Bragg,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ca/">California</a>
<cite>Advocate News</cite>, a reporter noted that Mullis
"talks about his Libertarian philosophy" as just one of "his wildly divergent 
interests. Government, he feels, is best suited to protect groups of 
people from outside interference, but ill-suited to dictate how 
individuals should lead their private lives."</p>

</ul>

<p>There may be others I don't have info on ...</p>

