<head>
<title>Firearms in the Home</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: late 1900's -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Firearms in the Home</h1>

<p>July 1994, from <a href="/revolution/by_name/D/DavidDeming.html">David
Deming</a>:</p>

<p>I have come to the conclusion that most advocates of gun control simply are
ignorant of the facts regarding the relationship between violence and 
firearms. Typical of these is the letter by Ellen Scheer which appeared in
the <cite>Oklahoman</cite> last Saturday, July 2. Ms. Scheer cites the
discredited study by Kellerman et al. which concluded that "in a home with
a gun....a family member is 43 times more likely to be shot than an 
intruder."  However, Ms. Scheer does not tell us that of the 43 shootings,
37 are suicides. We may reasonably conclude that these suicides would not
have been prevented by the absence of a firearm, because it is well 
known that gun availability does not influence suicide rates. For example,
private gun ownership in Japan is virtually unknown, yet the suicide rate
in Japan is twice that of the U.S..</p>

<p>There are two other flaws in the Kellerman study cited by Ms. Scheer. The
first of these is that Kellerman did not consider instances where a gun 
was used to ward off an anticipated criminal act but not fired, or was fired
and did not result in a death. Professor Gary Kleck of Florida State
University has estimated that guns are used for self defense against
criminals more than 2 million times a year.  In more than 98% of these 
cases the gun is not fired. Professor Kleck is a self-described liberal
Democrat and <a href="/revolution/by_name/A/ACLU.html">ACLU</a> member who has
never accepted any funding from the <a
href="/revolution/by_name/N/NRA.html">NRA</a>
or any other gun rights organization. Kleck's research is important in that
he is regarded by his colleagues as the leading expert on the subject of
firearms and violence.</p>

<p>For example, Kleck's book <cite>Point Blank:  Guns and Violence in
America</cite> was the winner of the 1993 Hindelang award from the American
Society of Criminology for "the book published in the past two years that
makes the most outstanding contribution to criminology". The other major 
flaw in the Kellerman study is that Kellerman groups the socially
dysfunctional with normal people, yet most familial gun violence is found
almost exclusively within a pathological subset of the general population:  
alcoholics, career criminals, drug addicts, etc. Professor Kleck has
concluded that for most people "the risks of a fatal gun accident are
negligible". When all of the defensive uses of firearms are factored in and
the suicides factored out, we find that a homeowner is 200 times more likely
to use a gun to prevent a criminal assault than to cause the death of an
innocent member of the household.</p>

<p>Ms. Scheer informs us that the U.S. has a teen-age murder rate seven times
higher than any nation in Western Europe. Presumably, Ms. Scheer is implying 
that the higher incidence of gun ownership in the U.S. causes the increased
violence. However, she does not consider the most obvious alternative
hypothesis:  that an increased level of violence leads to a higher level of
gun ownership for defensive purposes.  Gun ownership is only one of many
variables that affect violence levels in different countries, societies, and
cultures. When factors such as race and culture are taken in consideration,
it is usually found that increased gun ownership is correlated with lower
violence levels. For example, the homicide rate amongst individuals of
Japanese ancestry living in America is less than half that of Japanese in
Japan.</p>

<p>I agree with Ms. Scheer that "gun violence costs too much ... to allow it to
increase any further." However, the consensus amongst serious and unbiased
researchers is that the availability of guns amongst the general population
certainly does not cause violent crime, and probably is an inhibitor of such
crime. Ignorance is not a virtue, and gun control policies conceived in
ignorance are likely to increase suffering amongst the innocent, not 
alleviate it.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
