<head>
<title>The Committee for Waco Justice</title>
<!-- Place: Washington, DC (USA) -->
<!-- Time: December 1993 - ongoing April 1995 -->
</head>

<body>
<h1>The Committee for Waco Justice</h1>

<p>June 1995, from <a href="/revolution/by_name/M/CarolMoore.html">Carol
Moore</a>:</p>

<p>"The <a href="/revolution/by_name/C/CWJ.html">Committee for Waco Justice</a>
is working for an complete and thorough investigation of BATF and FBI crimes
against the Branch Davidian religious group near
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/tx/Waco.html">Waco</a>,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/tx/">Texas</a> and for
prosecution of responsible agents and officials.  We call for
freedom for the nine Branch Davidian prisoners sentenced to
243 years in prison for defending themselves against the
brutal BATF assault."</p>

<p>The CWJ has been active since at least December 1993, when Carol Moore
posted the following:</p>

<p>Our report on the massacre will demand:</p>

<ol>
<li><p>PROSECUTION OF ATF/FBI AGENTS:</p>

<p>At the end of the individual sections on ATF/FBI we will be
recommending prosecution of specific agents and officials under
the following two laws.</p>

<p>TITLE 18 SECTION 241-(18USC 241)-CONSPIRACY AGAINST THE RIGHTS OF
CITIZENS: If two or more persons conspire to injure, oppress, threaten,
or intimidate any citizen in the free exercise or enjoyment of
any right or privilege secured to him by the Constitution or laws
of the United States, or because of his having so exercised the
same; or if two or more persons go in disguise on the highway or
the premises of another, with intent to prevent or hinder his
free exercise or enjoyment of any right or privilege so secured- 
they shall be fined not more than $10,000 or imprisoned not more
than 10 years, or both: and if death results they shall be
subject to imprisonment for any term of years or for life.</p>

<p>TITLE 18 SECTION 242-(18USC242)-DEPRIVATION OF RIGHTS UNDER COLOR OF LAW:  
Whoever, under color of any law, statute, ordinance,
regulation, or custom, willfully subject any inhabitant of any
state, territory or district to the deprivation of any rights,
privileges, or immunities secured or protected by the
Constitution or laws of the United States, or to different
punishments, pains, or penalties, on account of such inhabitant
being an alien, or by reasons of his color, or race, than are
prescribed for the punishment of citizens, shall be fined not
more than $1,000 or imprisoned not more than one year, or both;
and if death results shall be subject to imprisonment for any
term of years or for life.  </p>

<li><p>Abolish BATF</p>

<p>Or at least put it under the same restrictions FBI has on
accumulating information on Americans.  According to <cite>Washington
Times</cite> article 11/2/93 "ATF chief vows to keep an eye on religious
cults," John Magaw, acting director of BATF said, "We're trying
to monitor them early in the game ... find out their history, their
background, makeup."  Looks like all BATF has learned from Waco
is to spy better and use bigger guns!</p>

<li><p>Restrict FBI and Other Federal Agent Powers</p>

<p>Federal agents' ability to serve warrants should be restricted or eliminated.
Restrict local/state/federal "multi-taskforces" or joint actions against
individuals or groups making them all defacto "co-conspirators" and giving no
possibility of independent investigation of wrongdoing. (Especially, local and
state law enforcement should not be deputized as federal marshals, as Texas
Rangers are who deal with Waco, in any situation where there is possibility of
wrongdoing by federal officers against citizens of state.)  </p>

<li><p>Congress Should Make A Clear and Constitutional Policy on "Armed
Groups"</p>

<p> Appendix G of the Treasury Dept. report on Waco is "A Brief
History of Federal Firearms Enforcement" and traces that history
from Shay's Rebellion (1786) through the civil war, prohibition,
and up to the present where they list several rightwing, tax
resisting, gun holding survivalists they've attacked and burned
out.  Waco was not the first.    </p>

<p> What is particularly of interest here is the statement: "The
raid by ATF agents on the Branch Davidian compound resulted from
its enforcement of contemporary federal firearms laws.  In a
larger sense, however, the raid fit within an historic, well-
established and well-defended government interest in prohibiting
and breaking up all organized groups that sought to arm or
fortify themselves ... From its earliest formation, the federal
government has actively suppressed any effort by disgruntled or
rebellious citizens to coalesce into an armed group, however
small the group, petty its complaint, or grandiose its ambition. 
The collection of large arsenals by organized groups lent itself,
ultimately, to the violent use of those weapons against the
government itself or portions of its citizenry. Indeed, federal
agents who tried to disband the groups frequently became the
targets."  (Appendix G, Page 7)</p>

<p> Finally, we know their true motivation for all this! So one thing that must
be demanded of Congress is an exact definition of "armed groups" -- how many
and what kinds of guns held by how many individuals in what kind of "group" is
considered an armed group which must be broken up?    </p>

</ol>

<hr>

<h2>Waco Resources</h2>

<p>June 1995, from <a href="/revolution/by_name/M/CarolMoore.html">Carol
Moore</a>:</p>

<ul>

<li><p>Carol Moore's <cite>The Davidian Massacre: Disturbing Questions
About Waco that Must Be Answered</cite>. Detailed analysis of
BATF/FBI/judge/prosecutor crimes and misconduct.  Available in
July 1995 from Gun Owners of America, 1-800-417-1486.</p></li>

<li><p>Available from Davidian Survivors.</p>
	<ul>
	<li>"DAY 51: The True Story of Waco" video review government crimes.
	<li>The "Inside Mount Carmel" video contains interviews with David
	Koresh and other Davidians during the siege.
	<li>Two books cover revelations during the trial of the Davidians,
	Jack DeVault's <cite>The Waco White Wash</cite> and Ken
	Fawcett's <cite>Blind Justice</cite>.
	<li>The February 28, 1993 911 audio tapes where Davidians' try to end
	the BATF attack.
	<li>8 audio tapes of David Koresh sermons and his unfinished tract
	"The Decoded Message of the Seven Seals of the Book Revelation."
	</ul>
<p>Contact Mount Carmel Survivors Memorial Fund, Inc. for price list.  P.O.
Box 120, Axtell, TX 76624. 817-754-2146.</p>

<li><p>KPOC-TV's video "The Waco Incident" contains both extraneous and lengthy
material and some excellent interviews and footage.  From Southwest Video
1-800-824-7566.</p></li>

<li><p>"Waco, the Big Lie" and "Waco, the Big Lie Continues" videos contain
some shocking and educational footage, despite some dubious facts and
theories.  Available from Freedom Forum books, 1800 Market Street,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ca/SanFrancisco.html">San
Francisco</a>,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ca/">CA</a> 94104.
4?5-864-0952.</p></li>

<li><p>January 1992 "Current Affair" "expose" on David Koresh and the
Davidians.  Available from Nine Network Australia, 22 Bendigo St, Richmond,
VIC 3121, <a href="/revolution/by_place/Oceania/Australia/">Australia</a>.
Tel: +61 3 4203232. $100 American.</p></li>

<li><p>Available from the Committee for Waco Justice:</p>
	<ul>
	<li>$5.00: Information pack</li>
	<li>$2.00 each: Two-inch pink buttons reading "Waco, Never Again"
		or "Free the Branch Davidians"</li>
	<li>$_______ contribution for educational and lobbying efforts.</li>

<p>Checks to Carol Moore <strong>only</strong>. (We remain too low budget
for a bank account.) Mail to: Box 65518 * Washington, D.C. 20035.</p>

</ul>

