<head>
<title>CCW in Louisiana</title>
<!-- Place: Louisiana (USA) -->
<!-- Date: May 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>CCW in <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/la/">Louisiana</a></h1>

<p>May 18, 1995, from the <a href="/revolution/by_name/N/NRA.html">NRA</a>:</p>

<p>Good news from Baton Rouge!  The State House approved H.B.  2442,
NRA-supported right-to-carry legislation, on an overwhelming 75-28 vote!
The bill now moves to the Senate for consideration. Another right to carry
bill, S.B. 1256, has already passed the Senate and awaits consideration by
the House Administration of Criminal Justice Committee. We'll keep you posted
as these bills progress.</p>

<p>Also, a Senate committee killed S.B. 1256, a bill opposed by NRA that would
have established mandatory storage procedures for firearms stored at home.</p>

<p>House Bill 2080, legislation that would exempt <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/la/NewOrleans.html">New Orleans</a>
from the statewide firearms pre-emption statute, will be heard in
the House Committee on Administration of Criminal Justice on
Tuesday, May 23 at 9:00 a.m.  This bill would allow New Orleans to
enact restrictive "gun control" ordinances in conflict with state
law, creating confusion and hardship for law-abiding gun owners.</p>

<hr>

<p>June 2, 1995, from another NRA alert:</p>

<p>The House Administration on Criminal Justice Committee
approved SB 886, NRA-backed right to carry reform legislation.
This bill now moves to the House floor for consideration.</p>

