<head>
<title>NYC CCW</title>
<!-- Place: New York City, New York (USA) -->
<!-- Time: account from 1994 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>NYC's Concealed-Carry Weapons (CCW) Permits</h1>

<p>1994, from Peter Venetoklis (<img src="/images/mail.gif" alt="[EMAIL]"><a
href="mailto:petev@gdstech.grumman.com">petev@gdstech.grumman.com</a>):</p>

<p>I figured the Libernet might be interested in what it takes to get a
pistol permit in the <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/ny/NewYorkCity.html">city of
New York</a>.  In order for me, average
citizen who does not have a business that moves lots of cash, to get a
gun, I have to apply for a "target" permit, meaning I can carry my
gun, unloaded and locked in a secure box with the ammo elsewhere, to
and from the pistol range.  I must belong to a pistol range in order
for them to consider my application.</p>

<p>The City requires the following:</p>
<ul>
<li>$170 Postal Money Order for application fee
<li>$50 Postal Money Order for fingerprints
<li>Notarized certification that I belong to a gun range/club
<li>Proof of Residence, e.g. Phone Bill
<li>Proof of Birthdate, e.g. Birth Certificate or Passport
<li>Two Head-and-Shoulders Photographs
<li>Signed and Notarized application, including history of residences, etc.
<li>A questionnaire describing what I want the gun for:
	<ul>
	<li>Personal Protection? (Correct answer:  No)
	<li>Keep gun loaded at home? (Correct answer: No)
	<li>Carry gun to shooting range?  (Yes)
	<li>How often do I want to shoot?  (2x/week)
	<li>How many guns do I want?  (3)
	<li>Do I want to keep guns locked up in house or business?  (house)
	</ul>
</ul>

<p>I used a "service" provided by Edelman's, a large gun retailer, to get
the paperwork done right, photos, notarized statements, etc.  They
also provide me with one year membership at three ranges.  Their fee
for all this stuff:  $295 plus tax.</p>

<p>I had to take a day off work and go to Police Headquarters in
Manhattan to personally hand in my application and get fingerprinted.
When I got there I had to answer a questionnaire about previous
arrests and summonses.  When I asked about parking tickets, the clerk
made me write a letter that I had paid all traffic and parking
tickets, and get it notarized.  Fortunately, she pointed me to a
notary nearby.  She then took three separate sets of fingerprints,
plus a thumbprint on the application.</p>

<p>Adding up all the expenses so far, I get about $546 plus gas, time off
work, aggravation, etc.  Sometime in the next few months I will get
called in for an interview where I will stress that my interest lies
strictly in target shooting, and I wouldn't use the gun for home
defense.  6 to 8 months from now, I will get my permit.  Renewal is
$125 every two years, plus about $100 per year for the pistol range
membership.  </p>

<p>I'm also guessing that after I get the license, they'll make me wait 5
more days to satisfy Brady.</p>

<p>I'm lucky I can (a) afford all these fees, and (b) take time off work
to do this.  I can't shake the impression that this stuff is the
equivalent of a poll tax intended to keep the poor from voting.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
