<head>
<title>Gunfire at the Waco Raid</title>
<!-- Place: Waco, Texas (USA) -->
<!-- Time: February 28, 1993 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Gunfire at the Waco Raid</h1>

<p>When BATF agents
<a href="/revolution/firearms/enforce/waco/">attacked the
Branch Davidians</a> at Waco, Texas, on February 28, 1993, they
served a search warrant for unregistered firearms with a full-scale
military attack.</p>

<h2>Firing From Helicopters</h2>

<p>The BATF used three helicopters in their raid: two small observation
craft containing National Guard pilots and one BATF agent, and a
Blackhawk with a National Guard pilot and eight BATF agents. As
the helicopters were all military craft, firing from them would
be illegal under the Posse Comitatus law.</p>

<p>Among the documents given to Congress for its reports was a
handwritten note by a Treasury Department review official who had
interviewed BATF agents. The note read: "HCs [helicopters] as a diversion. 
Simultaneous gunfire. Worked in Seattle. Three to four hundred
meters from boundary. Hover. Practiced at Hood."</p>

<p>One of the BATF agents in the helicopters said during the
House hearings that the agents in the Blackhawk had their weapons
loaded, and had been told they could fire in self-defense.</p>

<p>While the helicopter pilots denied circling Mt. Carmel,
a television camera crew testified that they witnessed the helicopters
do so. Television video of the raid apparently show bullets hitting
the roof of the building from above.</p>

<p>The Davidians called 911 during the raid to request a ceasefire.
The callers say that the helicopters are firing on them. During
later negotiations, firing from the helicopters is one of the
points of which the Davidians complain most. Surviving Davidians
claim that there were over a hundred bullet holes in the roof.</p>

<hr>

<p>Source: <a href="/revolution/by_name/C/CarolMoore.html">Carol Moore</a>.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
