<head>
<title>Ex-boyfriend Killed</title>
<!-- Place: Lebanon, Pennsylvania (USA) -->
<!-- Time: incident May 21, 1995; shooting May 1995? -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Ex-boyfriend Killed</h1>

<p>When Barbara Weaver ended her relationship with John Boyer III,
Boyer publicly threatened to kill her and himself. Weaver obtained
a protection-from-abuse order (restraining order) against Boyer,
barring him from her vicinity.</p>

<p>Weaver sought refuge in the
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/pa/Lebanon.html">Lebanon</a>,
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/pa/">Pennsylvania</a> home
of Brian Scott Mase. On May 21, 1995, Boyer showed up at the Mase home, and
Weaver called the police, who made him leave (but according to
the order were supposed to arrest him).</p>

<p>Boyer later returned to the Mase home. Mase retrieved his father's
M-1A carbine rifle and told him to leave. Instead, Boyer entered and
grabbed a wooden object, which Mase thought was a baseball bat, and
Weaver thought was a skateboard.</p>

<p>Mase fired one shot, hitting Boyer in the stomach and killing him.</p>

<p>Police arrested Mase for homicide, and a judge denied him bail. Mase
will spend at least six months in jail awaiting trial. His grandparents
have sold their home to help pay for his legal defense.</p>

<p>Mase's father decided to go to the Internet for help.
<img src="/images/www.gif" alt="[WWW]"><a
href="http://www.leba.net/~rickmase/">Richard Mase</a>
has put on the World Wide Web news stories and other information about
the case.</p>

<p>District Attorney Bradford Charles, not too happy about the Internet
site, asked the judge to bar Brian Mase and his attorney from talking
to Richard Mase. The judge ruled against Charles, allowing Mase to
continue his Internet presence.</p>

<p>Tax-deductible contributions for Brian Mase's defense can be sent to the
Gun Owners Foundation, 8001 Forbes Place, Suite 102, Springfield Va. 22151.
Write "Brian Mase" in the memo field of the check. Checks can also be sent
direct to Brian's dad, although they will not be tax deductible, at Brian
Mase Defense Fund, 254 S. 12th St., rear, Lebanon, Penn. 17042.</p>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
