<head>
<title>Cato Institute</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: 1978 - present -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Cato Institute</h1>

<p>The <a href="/revolution/by_name/C/Cato.html">Cato Institute</a> "think
tank" is perhaps the most influential libertarian organization in politics
today. Cato's policy recommendations have become especially well-heard in the
new Republican Congress.</p>

<p>Cato traces its origins to millionaire <a
href="/revolution/by_name/K/CharlesKoch.html">Charles Koch</a>, of Koch
Industries, the wealthiest privately-held company in the U.S. Koch spent
millions to found Cato and recruited then-Libertarian Party Chair <a
href="/revolution/by_name/C/EdCrane.html">Ed Crane</a> to head the new
organization.</p>

<hr>

<p>Sources:</p>
<ul>
<li>Nelson, Michael. "The New Libertarians." <cite>Saturday Evening
Post</cite>, 1 March 1980, 7:21-4.
</ul>

