<html>

<head>
<title>ACT New Zealand</title>
<!-- Place: New Zealand -->
<!-- Time: 1995 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>New Zealand Libertarians form Party</h1>

<p><a href="/revolution/by_place/Oceania/NewZealand/">New Zealand</a>
libertarians, including a former finance minister, have formed
ACT New Zealand, a libertarian-oriented political party.</p>

<p>New Zealand long was a bastion of the welfare state. Then, Sir Roger
Douglas, a Labour Party finance minister, began a series of libertarian
economic reforms in 1984 helping New Zealand become the fastest-growing
economy in the industrialized world.</p>

<p>One of the discouraging things about libertarianism is how many people
continue to oppose it in the face of overwhelming success. But I suppose it's
only to be expected from people who continue to support welfarism in the face
of overwhelming failure.</p>

<p>Douglas is widely respected outside New Zealand, but has high unfavorable
ratings inside the country. The press opposed his wide-ranging reforms, which
included privatizing the post office.</p>

<p>The new party's philosophy is spelled out in Douglas' new book,
<cite>Unfinished Business</cite>. ACT New Zealand wants to eliminate
government in health, education and pensions, and abolish the income tax.</p>

<p>Like many libertarian organizations, ACT New Zealand attracts not only
people dissatisfied with the major parties (Labour and National), but also
people who have never been involved in politics before.</p>

<p>Contact:</p>
<address>
Act New Zealand, Box 6860, Wellesley St, Auckland, New Zealand<br>
voice: 09 366 7640 (International calls: +64 9 366 7640)<br>
fax: 09 366 7643 (International calls: +64 9 366 7643)<br>
