<head>
<title>Famous Libertarians</title>
<!-- Place: world -->
<!-- Time: 1970's - present -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Famous Libertarians</h1>

<p>You know you've hit it big time when you've got actors and musicians
advocating your cause.</p>

<p>Famous libertarians include:</p>
<dl>
<p>
<dt><a href="/revolution/by_name/B/DaveBarry.html">Dave Barry.</a></dt>
<dd>The syndicated humorist supports the Libertarian Party and advocates
libertarian ideas frequently in his weekly humor column and his popular
books.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Penn Gillette.</dt>
<dd>Half of the magician duo Penn and Teller, Gillette is a Libertarian
Party supporter.</dd>

<p>
<dt>John Laroquette.</dt>
<dd>The popular actor who became famous with "Night Court" is
registered to vote as a Libertarian. On an irrelevant personal note,
he attended the same high school I did in New Orleans (though many
years earlier, and only briefly before being kicked out!).</dd>

<p>
<dt>Michael Moriarty.</dt>
<dd>The award-winning actor and pianist-composer advocates libertarian
goals. He condemns the federal government as an emerging police state, citing
<a href="/revolution/firearms/enforce/waco/">Waco</a> and
<a href="/revolution/firearms/enforce/rubyridge/">Ruby Ridge</a>
as examples, and he supports drug legalization. Moriarty is an Emmy, Tony
and Golden Globe award winning actor, as well as a classical and jazz
pianist with three CDs released.</dd>

<p>
<dt><a href="/revolution/by_name/S/HowardStern.html">Howard Stern</a>.</dt>
<dd>The nationally carried "shock jock" radio personality won the
Libertarian Party nomination for governor of New York (before he dropped out
of the race). Stern is a strong advocate of free speech and personal
freedom.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Mojo Nixon.</dt>
<dd>The rockabilly musician is a Libertarian Party supporter.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Ted Nugent.</dt>
<dd>The rock star (most famous for "Cat Scratch Fever") and avid sportsman
supports gun rights and endorsed a Libertarian Party candidate for U.S.
Senator in
<a href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/mi/">Michigan</a>.</dd>

<p>
<dt><a href="/revolution/by_name/O/PJORourke.html">P. J. O'Rourke.</a></dt>
<dd>Although the humorist calls himself a "Republican Party Reptile,"
it is hard to imagine a Republican advocating drugs and fast cars. O'Rourke
has written for <cite>National Lampoon</cite>, <cite>Car and
Driver</cite> and <cite>Rolling Stone</cite> magazines and is the
author of numerous books.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Kurt Russell.</dt>
<dd>The star of <cite>Escape from New York</cite>, <cite>Escape from
L.A.</cite>, <cite>Big Trouble in Little China</cite> and many more is
registered to vote as a Libertarian.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Barry Williams ("Dr. Demento").</dt>
<dd>The radio show host and collector of unusual recordings is a
Libertarian Party supporter.</dd>

<p>
<dt><a href="/revolution/by_name/P/VirginiaPostrel.html">Virginia Postrel.</a></dt>
<dd>Editor of <a href="/revolution/by_name/R/Reason.html"><cite>Reason</cite></a>
	magazine, the sixth largest political magazine in the U.S. Now
	that's she's appeared on Comedy Central's "Politically Incorrect"
	she gets a "famous" rating. :-)</dd>

<p>
<dt><a href="/revolution/science/nobel.html">Nobel Prize
	winners</a></dt>
<dd>Quite a few recipients of the Nobel Prize have been
libertarians, including economist <a
href="/revolution/by_name/F/MiltonFriedman.html">Milton Friedman</a>.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Science fiction writers.</dt>
<dd>Many science fiction authors are libertarian, including Robert Heinlein,
L. Neil Smith, J. Neil Schulman, Victor Koman and many others.</dd>
</dl>

<hr>

<h2>Kinda Sorta Maybes</h2>

<p>In addition to self-described libertarians, there are many famous
personalities who have expressed sympathy with libertarian ideas or
expressed those ideas themselves.</p>

<dl>
<p>
<dt>John Carpenter.</dt>
<dd>A television station called the <cite>Escape from L.A.</cite> director
a libertarian.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Hugh Downs.</dt>
<dd>Downs' commentary in the "Perspective" nationwide radio program has
included opposition to the drug war and Internet censorship, as well
as a call to have Harry Browne in the 1996 presidential debates.
"Some Americans who have read his book <cite>Why Government
Doesn't Work</cite> are wondering why they ever voted for those other
two parties," said Downs, after commenting favorably on the LP's longevity,
electoral successes and general beliefs.</dd>

<p>
<dt>David Letterman and Sandra Bernhardt.</dt>
<dd>Close call on this one. In 1988 on Late Night with David Letterman,
Letterman asked Berhnardt who she was voting for for president. Bernhardt
replied, "That Libertarian guy," and Dave said, "Yeah me too." Letterman
has generally been one to mock rather than support government agencies.</dd>

<p>
<dt>Mary Matalin.</dt>
<dd>The well-known Republican political commentator once said of Libertarian
presidential candidate Harry Browne, "I support Browne in the debates, he
has lots of good ideas, I don't agree with them all, and I'm not going to
vote for him ... or wait ... maybe I will vote for him!"</dd>

</dl>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
