<html>

<head>
<title>LP '94 Membership Plans</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1>Membership Strategy for 1994</h1>

<p>From <a href="/revolution/by_name/D/SteveDasbach.html">Steve Dasbach</a>,
responding to a post by Kevin Brooke:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>I found Joe's latest posting of membership statistics to be revealing.
First off, it shows that we are a long way off from Steve Dasbach's goal
of doubling membership by next year.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Kevin is right that we have a long way to go before we succeed in
doubling our membership/contributor base. However, when the
Executive Committee set that goal in October, we also developed
an action plan and budgeted the funds necessary to achieve it. In
December, that budget was approved by the entire LNC.</p>

<p>Our goal, as set by the Executive Committee, is to double our
contributor base (members and subscribers) prior to the 1996
convention. (My personal goal is to double it by the delegate
allocation deadline in 1995).</p>

<p>To achieve this kind of dramatic growth in our base of support,
we have to:</p>
<ol>
<li>Reduce the percentage of Libertarian Party contributors who
fail to renew each year;
<li>Increase the percentage of inquiries (either to LPHQ or the
800-number) who decide to join (or subscribe);
<li>Generate more inquiries;
<li>Aggressively work to return lapsed contributors to active status;
<li>Use direct mail to prospect for new members, and;
<li>Test and revise materials continuously to improve their effectiveness.
</ol>

<p>Our plan was to focus first on the failure of current
contributors to renew. The best data we have suggests that 40% of
contributors fail to renew each year. That means if we start the
year with 10,000 contributors, we must bring in 4000 new people
just to break even. It's hard to grow when you're losing people
that rapidly.</p>

<p>In the past, our membership growth activities have focused on
bringing in new members. That's like keeping a bleeding patient
alive by continuously transfusing new blood. We felt that it made
more sense to try to stop the bleeding first.</p>

<p>The best data we have indicates that the principal reason that
people fail to renew is the sense they have that we are not
making enough progress. We decided to tackle that issue in two
ways:</p>
<ol>
<li>Develop and implement activities (such as Project Healthy
Choice) that would generate tangible successes, and;
<li>Communicate our successes regularly to the membership through
LP News and our direct mail fundraising program.
</ol>

<p>Project Healthy Choice (PHC) got off the ground in November of
1993. Our vision of "small steps, big payoff" and commitment to
regularly communicate our successes to our contributors was
detailed in the December direct mail letter. The first PHC
successes were covered in the January issue of LP News and the
January direct mail letter detailed more success on a variety of
topics.</p>

<p>I believe we are already beginning to see the results in our
contributor statistics:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Date</th>	<th>Members</th><th>Subscribers</th>
	<th>Total contributors</th></tr>
<tr><td>2/28/93</td>	<td>11627</td>	<td>2609</td>	<td>14236</td></tr>
<tr><td>12/31/93</td>	<td>9565</td>	<td>1885</td>	<td>11450</td></tr>
<tr><td>1/31/94</td>	<td>9552</td>	<td>1898</td>	<td>11450</td></tr>
<tr><td>2/28/94</td>	<td>9473</td>	<td>1942</td>	<td>11415</td></tr>
<tr><td>3/31/94</td>	<td>9539</td>	<td>2009</td>	<td>11518</td></tr>
</table>

<p>From February to December 1993, we experienced an average net
loss of 279 contributors each month. From December 1993 to March
of 1994, our number of contributors has grown slightly. Since
there has been no significant increase in inquiries processed by
LPHQ during this time, it appears that we are experiencing a
significant increase in renewal rates.</p>

<p>National Director <a href="/revolution/by_name/W/PerryWillis.html">Perry
Willis</a> has also revised our entire cycle
of renewal letters and we are now able to track the percentage of
people who renew as a result of each letter.</p>

<p>The next release of our database program (scheduled for June '94)
will allow split-list testing of renewal letters, so we can
further improve their effectiveness.</p>

<p>The next step in our plan to is to increase the percentage of
inquiries to LPHQ and the 800 number who join the LP. Currently,
less than 10% of inquiries join the LP (the percentage varies
depending on the source of the inquiry). Based on his experience
in <a
href="/revolution/by_place/NorthAmerica/USA/nh/">New Hampshire</a>,
<a href="/revolution/by_name/W/BillWinter.html">Bill
Winter</a> believes that we should be able to
achieve a rate approaching 20% by improving the quality of the
materials we send to inquiries and by changing the way in which
we respond.</p>

<p>Until recently, 800-number inquiries were sent a slick brochure
with a cover letter signed by ex-National Director <a
href="/revolution/by_name/D/NickDunbar.html">Nick Dunbar</a>.
The letter did not make a membership pitch but instead indicated
that more information would be forthcoming. That information pack
and a copy of <cite>Liberty Today</cite> was supposed to be sent within a few
weeks. There have been many instances in the past where people
did not receive the information pack at all, or else it was sent
months after the initial inquiry. </p>

<p>The staffing and procedures at LPHQ have been improved to prevent
problems with information pack mailings. Bill Winter has revised
the content and improved the quality of the information pack and
a new first response letter has been written that asks the person
to join right away. Bill has also drafted a one page flyer (10
Answers to Commonly Asked Questions about the LP) that addresses
the most common reasons that people give for not joining. As soon
as it is approved by the Advertising and Publications Review
Committee (APRC), it will be added to the first response mailing.</p>

<p>Sometime this summer, we expect to replace the two part mailing
process with a single information pack mailing direct from the
800 number company. That means that inquiries will receive
everything they need to evaluate the LP and make a decision about
joining within days of their call. To do this, our current
materials have to be re-designed to fit the maximum size (6" by
9") and weight requirements of the 800-number company.</p>

<p>Now that we have increased our renewal rate, we will be turning
our attention to lapsed members. We hope that by communicating
our successes to them, we can get many to renew their commitment
to the LP just as our current members are doing.</p>

<p>Once we have confirmation that we have increased the rate at
which inquiries are joining the LP, we will be stepping up our
efforts to generate more inquiries. And, of course, we can
anticipate more inquiries as a result of 1994 campaigns.</p>

<p>In the meantime, we are preparing to mail (over the next few
months) membership prospecting letters to two mailing lists that
have generated hundreds of new members in the past. A test
mailing of 5000 has been already been printed and stuffed - it
should be in the mail by the end of next week. If successful, we
will mail the same letter to the rest of the list. The same
process will be followed for the other list.</p>

<p>Mailing successfully to untried lists requires the ability to do
split-list testing, which is scheduled for our next software
upgrade (June '94). By then, the first two mailings should be
completed.</p>

<p>The following phases of our membership growth plan will be
developed based on the data collected during these first few
months. We will expand what works, change what doesn't, and
document everything for the future.</p>

<p>Doubling our contributor base by the next convention is a
challenging goal, but I am convinced that, like achieving
universal ballot access in 1992, it can be done. The challenge
now is to do it.</p>

