<head>
<title>A-Z Spending Cuts</title>
<!-- Place: USA -->
<!-- Time: alert May 16, 1994 -->
</head>

<body>

<h1>Republicans Ask Libertarian Help for Spending Cuts</h1>

<p>Informational Alert for Libertarians<br>
from the National Libertarian Party Headquarters<br>
May 16, 1994<br></p>

<p>Friends:</p>

<p>You may have seen the press release issued recently by the National LP
office about the "A-Z Spending Cut Plan." In it, National Chair <a
href="/revolution/by_name/D/SteveDasbach.html">Steve Dasbach</a>
urged Libertarians to lobby for the bill, which could potentially slash
billions of dollars from the federal budget.</p>

<p>Here are the details of the bill, and some background information, in case
you would like to help lobby. More information will be in the next issue of
<cite>LP News</cite>, and the <cite>Liberty Pledge News</cite>.</p>

<p><a href="/revolution/by_name/W/BillWinter.html">Bill Winter</a><br>
Director of Communications<br>
Libertarian Party<br></p>

<hr>

<ul>
<li><p>THE SITUATION:
        The "A-Z Spending Cut Plan" - sponsored by Rep. Bill Zeliff (R-NH) and
Rep. Rob Andrews (D-NJ) - is being stonewalled in Congress by Speaker of the 
House Tom Foley.</p>

<p>Last August, a majority of House members - 160 Republicans and 74 
Democrats - signed a letter to Foley endorsing a special session to cut 
spending. However, Foley refused to act. Now Zeliff and Andrews are trying to 
gather the signatures of 218 House members on a discharge petition, which 
would bypass the leadership and force the bill onto the floor of the House.
</p>

<li><p>HOW THE LP GOT INVOLVED:
        The LP got involved with the bill when Chip Griffin, legislative 
assistant to Rep. Zeliff, called the National headquarters on May 11th to ask 
for assistance.</p>

<li><p>WHY THIS IS IMPORTANT: National Director <a
href="/revolution/by_name/W/PerryWillis.html">Perry Willis</a> said.
"As far as I know, the National 
LP has never been asked for help by a U.S. Congressman before. This is an 
excellent opportunity for us to become a more serious player in Washington 
politics."</p>

<li><p>THE DETAILS:
        The "A-Z Spending Cut Plan" consists of two parts:
<ul>
        <li>House Resolution 406, allocating 56 hours to debate proposals to 
reduce government spending. There would be an on-the-record "yes or no" vote 
on each specific spending cut. No tax increases could be considered.
        <li>House Bill 3266, which provides for automatic reductions in 
Congressional spending limits by the amount of the cuts.
</ul></p>

<li><p>WHAT YOU CAN DO:
        Call or write your Congressperson as soon as possible. Ask them if 
they have signed the discharge petition for the "A-Z Spending Cut Plan." If 
not, urge them to do so immediately.</p>

<p>        Here's how to contact your U.S. Representative in Washington DC:
        Write: The Hon. ______, U.S. House of Representatives, Washington DC 
20515.
        Call: The telephone switchboard for all members of Congress is (202) 
224-3121.</p>

</ul>

<hr><p align=center><font size=-1 color="#990000">
